# The Self-Hosting Journey

@meta {
  title: "The Self-Hosting Journey — Writing LATERALUS in LATERALUS"
  date: "2024-11-20"
  author: "bad-antics"
  tags: ["compiler", "self-hosting", "bootstrap", "internals"]
  reading_time: "10 min"
}

@heading level=1 {
  The Self-Hosting Journey
}

@subtitle {
  What it means to write a compiler in the language it compiles
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  What Is Self-Hosting?
}

@paragraph {
  A programming language is *self-hosted* when its compiler is written in
  the language itself. C compilers are written in C. Go is compiled by Go.
  Rust is compiled by Rust.
}

@paragraph {
  This milestone matters for practical and philosophical reasons:
}

@paragraph {
  *Practically*: a self-hosted compiler is the most comprehensive test of
  the language. If the language can express its own compiler — parsing,
  AST traversal, code generation, optimization — it can express anything.
}

@paragraph {
  *Philosophically*: self-hosting is the moment a language becomes real.
  It's the language proving it believes in itself enough to be its own
  foundation.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  The Bootstrap Problem
}

@paragraph {
  There's a chicken-and-egg problem: you can't compile LATERALUS code with
  a LATERALUS compiler until you have a LATERALUS compiler. The solution is
  a *bootstrap compiler* — a version of the compiler written in another language
  (in our case, Python) that can compile LATERALUS code, including the
  LATERALUS-written compiler.
}

@paragraph {
  The process has three stages:
}

@code lang=text {
  Stage 1: Bootstrap compiler (Python)
    → Can compile basic LATERALUS
    → Written and maintained by humans

  Stage 2: v2 compiler written in LATERALUS
    → Compiled by Stage 1 bootstrap
    → Produces Python code (or eventually native code)

  Stage 3: Self-hosted
    → v2 compiler compiled by v2 compiler
    → Bootstrap Python compiler no longer needed for production
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Where We Are Today
}

@paragraph {
  The LATERALUS v1.3.0 release includes the bootstrap directory:
  three files that form the beginning of the v2 self-hosted compiler,
  all written in LATERALUS:
}

@code lang=text {
  bootstrap/
    v2_lexer.ltl      — Tokenizes LATERALUS source code
    v2_parser.ltl     — Builds the AST from token streams
    v2_codegen.ltl    — Generates output from the AST
}

@paragraph {
  These files can be run by the current Python bootstrap compiler.
  They're not production-ready yet — they don't handle every edge case,
  and they're significantly slower than the Python implementation.
  But they're *real*: they correctly parse and process LATERALUS programs.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  What the v2 Lexer Looks Like
}

@paragraph {
  The v2 lexer is itself a pipeline. Token recognition flows naturally:
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  fn tokenize(source: str) -> list {
    source
      |> split_chars()
      |> scan(lex_step, LexState.new())
      |> filter((tok) => tok.kind != TokenKind.Whitespace)
      |> filter((tok) => tok.kind != TokenKind.Comment)
      |> collect()
  }
}

@paragraph {
  This is the key insight: when you write a lexer in a pipeline-oriented
  language, the lexer *becomes* a pipeline. The structure of the code
  mirrors the structure of the algorithm.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Challenges We've Encountered
}

@heading level=3 {
  Challenge 1: Recursive Types
}

@paragraph {
  AST nodes reference other AST nodes. An @code{IfExpr} contains a
  condition expression, a then-body, and an else-body — all of which
  are themselves expressions. Without algebraic data types or generics
  (coming in v1.5), we represent these with tagged maps.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // v2 AST nodes as tagged maps
  fn make_if_expr(cond, then_body, else_body) {
    {
      "kind":      "if_expr",
      "condition": cond,
      "then":      then_body,
      "else":      else_body,
    }
  }
}

@heading level=3 {
  Challenge 2: Error Recovery
}

@paragraph {
  A production compiler needs to report *multiple* errors, not just the
  first one. Error recovery — continuing to parse after an error is found —
  is subtle to implement correctly. Our v2 parser currently stops at the
  first error. Resilient parsing is a v1.5 goal.
}

@heading level=3 {
  Challenge 3: Performance
}

@paragraph {
  The Python bootstrap compiler has ~15 years of CPython optimization behind
  it. The LATERALUS v2 compiler, transpiled to Python, is slower. This is
  expected and acceptable for now — correctness before performance.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  The Road to Full Self-Hosting
}

@paragraph {
  Full self-hosting — where LATERALUS produces native machine code and
  compiles itself to native — is a v2.0 goal. The path:
}

@code lang=text {
  v1.3  → Bootstrap in Python; v2 lexer/parser/codegen in LATERALUS (partial)
  v1.4  → v2 compiler handles all language features except generics
  v1.5  → Generics + ADTs; v2 compiler handles full language
  v2.0  → v2 compiler compiles itself; Python bootstrap retired
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Why This Matters for Users
}

@paragraph {
  You might wonder: why should users care about the compiler implementation
  language?
}

@paragraph {
  The answer is: the v2 compiler will be easier to contribute to. Right now,
  improving the LATERALUS compiler requires knowing Python well. Once the
  compiler is self-hosted, it requires only knowing LATERALUS.
}

@paragraph {
  The language becomes its own best tool. Everything — from the runtime to
  the tooling to the compiler itself — is written in LATERALUS.
  That's the goal. Spiral out. Keep going.
}

@footer {
  Filed under: compiler, self-hosting · November 2024
}

